			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				The case began back in 2002, when the PBS series Frontline aired a piece about pornography in america.  In part of it, they featured filming by producers/directors Rob Black (Rob Zicari) and his wife Lizzy Borden (Janet Ramano).    In an interview, Rob Black (really Rob Zicari) more or less taunted law enforcement agencies to come after him.  They did.
<br />

<br />
Postal inspectors, reportedly allerted to the Extreme Associates (Mr. Zicari's company) website by the Los Angeles District Attorney's office, joined <a href="http://extreme-2.com/enter.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">the site</a>and viewed several video clips.  They later, working with other inspectors in western pennsylvania (a place they apparently thought would benefit them at trial using the "community standards" doctrine) bought several videos which were shipped by US mail.
<br />

<br />
Both Mr. Zicari and his wife were arrested and subsequently indicted on multiple obscenity charges.
<br />

<br />
Last week, a federal judge dismissed the case, citing both a 1969 and more recent Supreme Court ruling.  In 2003, the high court recognized a right to privacy with respect to sexual relations in <span style="font-style: italic">Lawrence v. Texas,</span> striking down a state law banning sodomy.  Some conservatives at the time were alarmed by the ruling, fearing that its broad language would extend to more issues.  In this case, they were right.
<br />

<br />
U.S. District Judge Gary L. Lancaster basically stated in his ruling (I'm baseing this from press reports as I've been unable to locate the complete text) that the right to possess obscene materials (the 1969 court case) was meaningless if no one could legally distribute them.  This is something the high court has never found.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">We find that the federal obscenity statutes burden an individual's fundamental right to possess, read, observe and think about what he chooses in the privacy of his own home by completely banning the distribution of obscene materials.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
My own opinions about this are pretty straightforward.  Before VCRs, porn was shown in movie theaters.  At that time, the "local community standards" doctrine made sense.  In the era of the internet, it does not make sense for any community in the US to be able to dictate to all other communities what they can or cannot view in the privacy of their own home.
<br />

<br />
While the videos in question (which apparently have been and still are available from Extreme Associations) could likely be offensive to the majority of people, if they were produced by consenting adults and distributed to consenting adults, I have no problem with them.  I think the judge did exactly the right thing.
<br />

<br />
From looking over new reports, I've learned that in the last 2 years one couple in Ohio (or maybe West Virginia) and one in Texas were both tried and found guilty for doing essentially the same thing as Extreme does (make and sell dirty movies).  In both cases, the parties were sentenced to years in jail.  I don't believe this is effective use of law enforcment or our courts, not to mention scarce jail cells.  I'd rather the cells be reserved for robbers, murders, and rapists.
<br />

<br />
That said, I would be remiss if I didn't mention one of the videos that was the subject of the indictment.  It was a collection of scenes simulating rape.  It was quite violent.  During its filming, the Frontline documentary crew actually walked out.  Not my cup of tea.  Still, who am I to tell someone they can't watch it?<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
